Name: nytimes
Text: “I need people to hear my voice.” Youth-led demonstrations after George Floyd’s death have energized a diverse group of young Americans across the U.S.

Name: nytimes
Text: 8 correctional officers have filed complaints with the Minnesota Department of Human Rights saying that people of color who work in the jail were initially barred from guarding Derek Chauvin, the officer accused of killing George Floyd

Name: nytimes
Text: In the wake of outrage over George Floyd’s death, the names of other men and women killed in confrontations with the police across the U.S. are receiving renewed attention from protesters, local newspapers and prosecutors https://nyti.ms/3dlpWjp

Name: nytimes
Text: "It has surprised me, and it gives me hope. I thought what I had done was in vain." The past several weeks, as protests over the killing of George Floyd rippled through U.S. cities, have left veterans of the civil rights era with trepidation and hope.

Name: nytimes
Text: Corporate America has pledged millions of dollars to social justice efforts since the killing of George Floyd. But some businesses have gone further, committing to concrete changes. Here is a list of some of the promises made.

Name: nytimes
Text: The Houston undercover officer who arrested George Floyd in 2004 over a $10 drug deal is at the center of one of the biggest police scandals in the city’s history. Thousands of his cases are under review, including Floyd's.

Name: nytimes
Text: Prosecutors said they were wrong by a minute when they described how long a police officer pinned George Floyd to the ground. Activists said the precise time is irrelevant. “The bottom line is, it was long enough to kill him, long enough to execute him.”

Name: nytimes
Text: The first black, openly transgender woman elected in the U.S. represents an area of Minneapolis near where George Floyd was arrested. “That’s where I live,” said Councilwoman Andrea Jenkins, “at the intersection of LGBT politics and racial injustice.”

Name: nytimes
Text: "I am asking you to help us, black people in America.” George Floyd’s brother, Philonise Floyd, called for the U.N. Human Rights Council to create an independent commission to study the killing of black people by the police in the U.S. Read more. https://nyti.ms/2ACW2Ke

Name: nytimes
Text: A Massachusetts man has been charged with sending emails that contained threats of violence and racial slurs to Danielle Outlaw, the police commissioner in Philadelphia, during the city’s protests over the death of George Floyd, the authorities said

Name: nytimes
Text: "It was the shock that I needed to finally wake up." The death of George Floyd in Minneapolis sparked protests around the world. In France, protesters gathered to call for the country to take account of racial differences and discrimination. Read more. https://nyti.ms/2YJizwC

Name: nytimes
Text: In 2 weeks, an idea from West Dakota, a drag queen in Brooklyn, blossomed into one of the most striking demonstrations that New York has seen since the killing of George Floyd. Thousands of people gathered in a sea of white.

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd’s killing unleashed a sweeping challenge to American racism in every state. See how the protests unfolded across the country.

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd's death has unleashed one of the most explosive trials of American racism in modern times. See more of how a movement calling for justice reached every corner of the nation. http://nyti.ms/2UGX3rd

Name: nytimes
Text: It continued that way. Within a week of George Floyd's killing, there were protests in 1,000 cities across the U.S. http://nyti.ms/2UGX3rd

Name: nytimes
Text: Within 24 hours of George Floyd’s killing, demonstrations were organized in 5 U.S. cities, with protesters chanting the names of black people subjected to police brutality. https://nyti.ms/2UGX3rd

Name: nytimes
Text: On any given day, the protesters spill out onto the streets. They march. They kneel. They sing. They cry. They pray. They light candles. George Floyd’s death has sparked protests across all 50 states. This is how the movement spread.

Name: nytimes
Text: Even if the former Minneapolis police officer Derek Chauvin is found guilty of murdering George Floyd, he will qualify to receive what could amount to around $50,000 a year in state pension payments. But how much of that money he will see is less certain.

Name: nytimes
Text: Joe Biden said the killing of George Floyd in police custody is having a larger global impact than the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.’s assassination in 1968. “Look at the millions of people marching around the world,” he said. https://nyti.ms/2YtgZPC

Name: nytimes
Text: None of the people charged with serious federal crimes amid the unrest following the killing of George Floyd have been linked so far to antifa, despite claims by President Trump

Name: nytimes
Text: "All these people are different colors, from different places, coming together for a purpose. I feel like the world should be like that." The memorial to George Floyd in Minneapolis has become a place to gather and reflect about race.

Name: nytimes
Text: Philonise Floyd, brother of George Floyd, testified before the U.S. House Judiciary Committee on Wednesday https://nyti.ms/2UucSBK

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd’s brother, Philonise Floyd, made an impassioned plea to Congress on Wednesday to enact sweeping changes to law enforcement in America to address police brutality and systemic racism. “This is 2020,” he said. “Enough is enough.”

Name: nytimes
Text: A Christopher Columbus statue was tossed into a city lake in Richmond, Virginia, this week and another effigy of the explorer in Boston had its head removed as protesters angered by the death of George Floyd directed their frustration at public monuments.

Name: nytimes
Text: “I’m here to ask you to make it stop," George Floyd’s brother, Philonise Floyd, pleaded with Congress on Wednesday at a House committee hearing to address police brutality and systemic racism. "Stop the pain." Read more here: https://nyti.ms/2BRx0qN

Name: nytimes
Text: “He didn’t deserve to die over $20. I am asking you, is that what a black man’s life is worth?” George Floyd’s brother Philonise Floyd is testifying before Congress. Watch live here.

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd’s brother Philonise Floyd will testify before Congress at a House hearing on police accountability and racial bias in law enforcement today, a day after George was laid to rest. Latest updates: https://nyti.ms/3fbvrm1

Name: nytimes
Text: Maurice Gordon moved to the U.S. from Jamaica to attend college. He was shot and killed by a white officer after a traffic stop in New Jersey, 2 days before the killing of George Floyd. “I have zero trust in the American system,” Gordon’s sister said.

Name: nytimes
Text: "We all loved him": Family, friends and hundreds of other mourners filled a Houston church more than 2 weeks after George Floyd’s death powered sprawling protests across America against racism. Read more. https://nyti.ms/3f99UdH

Name: nytimes
Text: Calling on the U.S. to "reconcile" for the country's record of mistreatment of black Americans, Rep. Al Green of Texas said on Tuesday that George Floyd's only crime "was that he was born black." https://nyti.ms/3cQnH7n

Name: nytimes
Text: Houston Mayor Sylvester Turner announced at the funeral service for George Floyd that he would sign an executive order banning police chokeholds or strangleholds. Read more: https://nyti.ms/2Yi8err

Name: nytimes
Text: “Lives like George’s will not matter until someone pays the cost for taking their lives,” the Rev. Al Sharpton said at George Floyd’s funeral in Houston on Tuesday. https://nyti.ms/3faMO6e

Name: nytimes
Text: The Rev. Al Sharpton is delivering a eulogy for George Floyd in Houston now. Watch the service live:

Name: nytimes
Text: Joe Biden offered his condolences to George Floyd's family, saying he understood the weight of grieving in public. “It is a burden,” he said in a video message, “a burden that is now your purpose, to change the world for the better.” http://nyti.ms/2Yhi50P

Name: nytimes
Text: Hours before the funeral started, flowers piled up under a framed photo of George Floyd. “That could be my father, that could be my cousin, my brother,” said Arion Ford, 27, a community organizer and a friend of the family’s, while choking back tears.

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd was remembered at his funeral as a 1993 graduate of Jack Yates High School, where he played on the basketball team as a 6’6” power forward "able to dunk with both hands." You can watch the service here: https://nyti.ms/2Yhi50P

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd wanted to "touch the world," a childhood friend of his said. "He could not have imagined that this is the tragic way people would know his name." He will be laid to rest today beside his mother.

Name: nytimes
Text: The outrage after George Floyd was killed in police custody led to mass protests, day and night, for weeks. The demonstrations reflect the depth of frustration borne of years of watching black people die at the hands of police or vigilantes while calls for change went unmet.

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd’s funeral is now underway in Houston. It will include a eulogy from the Rev. Al Sharpton. You can watch live here: https://nyti.ms/2Yhi50P

Name: nytimes
Text: Maurice Gordon, 28, was shot by a white officer after a traffic stop on the Garden State Parkway, 2 days before the death of George Floyd in police custody. “I just need answers: Why did they kill my son?” Mr. Gordon's mother said on Monday.

Name: nytimes
Text: "I think the same way that George Floyd was asking for a breath, this city is asking for a breath." Protests over George Floyd’s death have reached small towns like Petal, Mississippi, where neighbors are confronting one another and talking about racism.

Name: nytimes
Text: From “I want to touch the world” to “I can’t breathe”: George Floyd had big plans for life. Today he will be buried next to his mother. https://nyti.ms/3h3FH1k

Name: nytimes
Text: After weeks of protests and calls for justice, George Floyd, the man whose death in police custody gave rise to an international movement and whose last words — “I can’t breathe” — have been a rallying cry, will be laid to rest in Houston. Latest updates: https://nyti.ms/2AVSEde

Name: nytimes
Text: Bail was set on Monday at up to $1.25 million for Derek Chauvin, the white former Minneapolis police officer charged with murder in the killing of George Floyd. Live updates about nationwide protests:

Name: nytimes
Text: Amid widespread protests over police brutality after the death of George Floyd, some federal and local officials blamed outsiders for stoking violence. Similar claims were made during the civil rights movement.

Name: nytimes
Text: Joe Biden “does not believe that police should be defunded,” a spokesman for his campaign said Monday. The statement comes as “defund the police” has emerged as a rallying cry following the killings of George Floyd and Breonna Taylor.

Name: nytimes
Text: Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer charged with murder in the killing of George Floyd, is expected to appear in a Minnesota courtroom on Monday afternoon

Name: nytimes
Text: Congress prepared to start debating a reform package aimed at addressing some of the concerns at the heart of protests that have swept the U.S. since George Floyd was killed in police custody 2 weeks ago. Latest updates: https://nyti.ms/2UlXO8S

Name: nytimes
Text: Senator Mitt Romney marched with demonstrators toward the White House on Sunday, appearing to be the first Republican senator to join the thousands across the country protesting the death of George Floyd in police custody

Name: nytimes
Text: Officials at Wichita State University Tech canceled the airing of Ivanka Trump’s prerecorded commencement speech after students and faculty members condemned the Trump administration’s handling of protests calling for justice for George Floyd

Name: nytimes
Text: Many cultural institutions have released statements about racial justice after the killing of George Floyd. Some of their public messages have been commended as better than silence; others have been criticized as tone deaf and too little too late.

Name: nytimes
Text: Thousands gathered in Washington, D.C., on Saturday to protest George Floyd’s death, racism and police brutality. From speeches to line dances, here’s what we saw and whom we met. https://nyti.ms/2BBtHUw

Name: nytimes
Text: Joe Biden will travel to Houston to meet with the family of George Floyd on Monday

Name: nytimes
Text: Mourners gathered on Saturday for a memorial service and public viewing for George Floyd in North Carolina, the state where he was born https://nyti.ms/3dGbpzK

Name: nytimes
Text: A 10th day of protests against police brutality and racism filled the streets of New York City on Saturday, with thousands of people gathering and marching in demonstrations set off by the killing of George Floyd. Follow the latest from New York here.

Name: nytimes
Text: Peaceful protesters came together in Washington, D.C., as another weekend of demonstrations unfolded across the U.S. in response to the killing of George Floyd. Read the latest updates here. https://nyti.ms/2Yc9n3X

Name: nytimes
Text: Marchers around the world turned out to oppose racism and stand in solidarity with American protesters calling for justice in the death of George Floyd https://nyti.ms/2zeeW9w

Name: nytimes
Text: Thousands of protesters gathered across the U.S. for another day of demonstrations over the death of George Floyd. Live updates: https://nyti.ms/2Y7KLJl

Name: nytimes
Text: First his friend Philando Castile was killed by the police. Then George Floyd. Now the activist and organizer John Thompson is running for office in Minnesota: "I'm a black man and I could suffer the same fate." Watch the video:

Name: nytimes
Text: President Trump, hailing a dip in the unemployment rate, said Friday that it was a “great day” for Americans and for George Floyd. The comments drew immediate criticism, and he ignored a question from a reporter who asked why it was a great day for Floyd. https://nyti.ms/3dAtxLq

Name: nytimes
Text: Thousands of demonstrators poured into streets across the U.S. for the 10th night of protest over the killing of George Floyd. Here were some of the scenes from around the country. https://nyti.ms/309PYTJ

Name: nytimes
Text: A local news report said protesters challenged the L.A. police chief for suggesting looters were somewhat responsible for George Floyd’s death. He apologized to the crowd and asked, “Will you accept my apology?” Some people in the crowd shouted, “No.”

Name: nytimes
Text: Protesters booed New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio during his remarks at a memorial for George Floyd in Brooklyn on Thursday. https://nyti.ms/3gTko2s

Name: nytimes
Text: A Hennepin County district judge considered and denied requests for reduced bail for 3 former Minneapolis police officers charged with aiding in George Floyd’s death. Bail was set at $750,000 each with certain conditions. https://nyti.ms/3cxCJ1F

Name: nytimes
Text: At a memorial in Minneapolis for George Floyd, the Rev. Al Sharpton tied Floyd's death to treatment many black Americans have experienced for generations. “It’s time for us to stand up in George’s name and say get your knee off our necks,” Sharpton said. https://nyti.ms/2UdmPDc

Name: nytimes
Text: A memorial for George Floyd is underway in Minneapolis, led by the Rev. Al Sharpton. Watch the service live:

Name: nytimes
Text: Senate Democrats on Thursday held a moment of silence lasting 8 minutes and 46 seconds, the amount of time that a police officer pressed his knee into George Floyd's neck. A handful of senators knelt on the marble floor during the moment of silence. https://nyti.ms/372ikRq

Name: nytimes
Text: The Minneapolis Police Department has released personnel records of the 4 former officers charged in George Floyd’s killing. Though heavily redacted, the documents reveal details of the officers’ lives before and during their time on the force.

Name: nytimes
Text: After a 9th day of protests across the U.S., thousands of people planned to gather in Minneapolis for the first of 6 days of memorials for George Floyd Latest updates: https://nyti.ms/2U8OC7I

Name: nytimes
Text: At a time when funeral gatherings are rare because of the coronavirus, a memorial service will honor George Floyd, whose death in police custody has provoked global outrage. The Rev. Al Sharpton will give the eulogy.

Name: nytimes
Text: Los Angeles officials estimated that there have been at least 3,000 arrests during the protests over the killing of George Floyd that began more than a week ago. Live updates of ongoing protests across the U.S.: https://nyti.ms/2Bwrrhq

Name: nytimes
Text: All officers involved in the killing of George Floyd have now been charged. Many protesters said the new charges would not quell the demonstrations, which were seeking broader systemic changes to the nation’s justice system.

Name: nytimes
Text: A witness who was in George Floyd’s car during his fatal encounter with a police officer said that Floyd tried to defuse the tensions with the police and in no way resisted arrest. “I could hear him pleading, ‘Please, officer, what’s all this for?’”

Name: nytimes
Text: A longtime friend of George Floyd who was in the passenger seat of Floyd’s car when he was arrested said on Wednesday night that Floyd attempted to defuse the tensions with the police and did not resist

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd had the coronavirus in early April, a full autopsy report from the Hennepin County medical examiner revealed, and continued to test positive at the time of his death https://nyti.ms/305Ist6

Name: nytimes
Text: “We all must shine a spotlight on the immorality of racial discrimination. But violence, whether spontaneous or consciously incited, is not a solution,” former President Jimmy Carter said in response to protests following George Floyd’s killing. https://nyti.ms/2XTLXQy

Name: nytimes
Text: Watch Live: Former President Barack Obama is giving his first on-camera comments about the killing of George Floyd and protests over police brutality sweeping across the U.S.

Name: nytimes
Text: “We cannot tolerate or turn a blind eye to racism and exclusion in any form and yet claim to defend the sacredness of every human life,” Pope Francis said on Wednesday, joining other world leaders in speaking out after George Floyd’s killing

Name: nytimes
Text: Breaking News: 3 officers have been charged with aiding and abetting Derek Chauvin, whose charge in the killing of George Floyd has been raised to second-degree murder.

Name: nytimes
Text: What began as a protest over George Floyd's death in police custody in Minneapolis has grown into a nationwide movement across the United States, with diverse activists, tactics and goals

Name: nytimes
Text: For many black people in Minneapolis, seeing police use force like the kind that killed George Floyd is disturbingly common. Our analysis of the city's own figures shows why: City police use force against black people at 7 times the rate as white people.

Name: nytimes
Text: A U.S.S. Reno flag, which was stolen from the City Hall in Reno during protests, was returned with an anonymous note attached: “Needed protecting. Looters were flag burning. RIP George Floyd.”

Name: nytimes
Text: “This is about a hundred years’ worth of intentional segregation and institutionalized racism.” As protests about the death of George Floyd enter a second week, we speak with the leader of the city where they began. Listen to today's episode of The Daily.

Name: nytimes
Text: The Minneapolis school board voted on Tuesday to sever ties with the city’s police department, a pointed response to the death of George Floyd

Name: nytimes
Text: George Floyd’s death continues to resonate far beyond Minneapolis, as protesters defied curfews Tuesday in cities across the U.S. https://nyti.ms/2z1eVWk

Name: nytimes
Text: "I'm here for my baby, and I’m here for George, because I want justice for him." Roxie Washington, George Floyd's girlfriend, talks about their 6-year-old daughter, Gianna, growing up without her father. https://nyti.ms/30ew6Px

Name: nytimes
Text: Kennetta Hollivay’s Dollar & Up market is a block-and-a-half from the spot where George Floyd died in Minneapolis. She has lived in the neighborhood her whole life, and said she felt compelled to join the protests. https://nyti.ms/3eHbzH6

Name: nytimes
Text: Candice Elder said she saw the death of George Floyd in the context of the constant sting of racism in her work with homeless people. One quarter of Oakland’s population is black. Yet 70% of the homeless people are African-American. https://nyti.ms/3eHbzH6

Name: nytimes
Text: Rashaad Dinkins was 12 when unrest broke out in Ferguson. He remembers watching the news, knowing that black people were being killed. When George Floyd was killed just a few blocks from where Dinkins lives in Minneapolis, he knew he had to be a part of the moment.

Name: nytimes
Text: In the week since George Floyd’s death, U.S. cities have been gripped by dissent. We asked protesters from across the country what inspired them to take to the streets.

Text: In Opinion Join @CharlesMBlow to discuss his @nytopinion column on George Floyd’s killing and the protests https://nyti.ms/2zNodFU

Name: nytimes
Text: Looting in Manhattan's central business district on Monday marred otherwise peaceful protests by thousands of people across New York City in the wake of George Floyd's death

Name: nytimes
Text: On the 7th day of largely peaceful protests over the death of George Floyd, tear gas and flash grenades were deployed against protesters outside the White House as military helicopters swept low over the streets. Follow the latest updates: https://nyti.ms/2MjE41h

Name: nytimes
Text: The New York Knicks won't make a statement on the death of George Floyd, the franchise’s owner told employees. The decision makes the Knicks an exception in a league where players and coaches have called for change on social media and joined protests.

Name: nytimes
Text: Demonstrations in many California cities have taken place to protest the death of George Floyd. Follow live updates: https://nyti.ms/36SSvmM

Text: After weeks of virtual events, Joe Biden on Monday met with community leaders at Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church, a black church in Delaware, as the U.S. entered another day of unrest in response to the killing of George Floyd

Text: Terrence Floyd, George Floyd’s brother, spoke at the scene of his brother's death in Minneapolis. Latest updates: https://nyti.ms/36VniPB

Name: nytimes
Text: A number of retailers, including Target, Walmart, and CVS, have temporarily closed some stores as protests and looting spread across the U.S. in the wake of the death of George Floyd https://nyti.ms/2XljBQc

Text: Gov. Andrew Cuomo said a curfew would be adopted in New York City after violence marred protests over the death of George Floyd https://nyti.ms/3gKOuoI

Text: A series of memorial services for George Floyd are being planned in Minneapolis, where he died, and in Houston, where he spent much of his life https://nyti.ms/36PEw0R

Name: nytimes
Text: “They’re Going to Kill Me,” flew over New York. “Please I Can’t Breathe,” circled above Detroit. “My Neck Hurts,” sailed in Dallas. In aerial demonstrations, the artist Jammie Holmes displayed George Floyd’s final words above cities across the U.S.

Name: nytimes
Text: The Minnesota Freedom Fund raised about $20 million within 4 days following the killing of George Floyd. People around the world donated to the fund, which posts bail for low-income people and protesters in Minneapolis.

Name: nytimes
Text: In Syria, 2 artists painted a mural on the shell of a ruined building that read “I Can’t Breathe” and “No to Racism.” Read more about global reaction to George Floyd’s death: https://nyti.ms/2Ayn0Sz

Name: nytimes
Text: Dispatches from cities across the U.S. being rocked by protests over police brutality after the death of George Floyd. Listen to today's episode of The Daily.

Text: The New York Times has reconstructed how George Floyd was killed in police custody. Security footage, witness videos and official documents show how a series of actions by police officers turned fatal. (This video contains scenes of graphic violence.)

Name: nytimes
Text: In photos: A nation in protest. Anger over the death of George Floyd, who was killed in police custody in Minneapolis, engulfed cities from coast to coast across the U.S. https://nyti.ms/2AvQyk4

Name: nytimes
Text: Fires burned outside the White House. There were widespread reports of looting and clashes with the police in cities across the U.S. after another day of peaceful protests over the killing of George Floyd descended into mayhem. Latest updates: https://nyti.ms/2ZTxsPm

Name: nytimes
Text: It was the 6th day of nationwide unrest in the U.S. since George Floyd was killed in police custody last week. Protesters defied curfews and several governors mobilized the National Guard. For live updates: https://nyti.ms/3coBIc6

Text: After weeks of being cooped up to stay alive, thousands of New Yorkers have taken to the streets to protest the death of George Floyd. Here are images from 4 days of protest. https://nyti.ms/2Xl0LZq

Name: nytimes
Text: The New York Times front page for Monday, June 1. The fury that has seized Minneapolis, where the death of George Floyd while in police custody set off days of protests, has swept across the country. For live updates: https://nyti.ms/3gFNuST

Name: nytimes
Text: Target says it will temporarily close or shorten the hours of about 200 stores in the U.S. as protests spread across the country. The Target store near where George Floyd died in Minneapolis was badly damaged last week.

Name: nytimes
Text: “I can make some money again,” said Kester Wubben, whose budding mail and printing business in Minneapolis may not survive the damage done during the protests. "But you can’t start George Floyd’s life back over. It’s ended.”

Text: Protests over police violence and racism have erupted in at least 75 cities across the U.S. after George Floyd died in police custody. Scenes from the streets:

Text: Video: Protests broke out across the country in response to the death of George Floyd. In Los Angeles, protesters shut down freeways and faced off with police officers.

Text: Thousands of people protesting police violence and the death of George Floyd have taken to the streets of New York City for a third day in marches across Harlem, Brooklyn, Queens, and outside Trump Tower in Manhattan

Text: Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz said he's activating all of the state's available National Guard troops — up to 13,200 — in response to protests ignited by George Floyd's death in Minneapolis. Follow the latest: http://nyti.ms/2MfeWZK

Name: nytimes
Text: “George Floyd was begging, saying he couldn’t breathe, saying please, please,” Jeanine Pirro said on Fox & Friends. “This man who put his knee on the neck of George Floyd does not deserve to be free in this country.”

Name: nytimes
Text: Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms said when she saw George Floyd die, “I hurt like a mother would hurt.” But she said the demonstrations in Atlanta were not in the spirit of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. “We are better than this.”

Name: nytimes

Text: Investigators have recommended misconduct charges against 3 NYPD officers who were involved in a violent arrest. One of the officers sat and knelt on a man in a maneuver similar to the one that led to the death of George Floyd in Minneapolis.

Name: nytimes
Text: Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer who pressed his knee into George Floyd's neck for about 8 minutes, has been charged with murder and manslaughter. Prosecutors said the investigation into 3 other officers at the scene is ongoing. http://nyti.ms/2U7o72T

Name: nytimes

Text: Breaking News: Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer who pressed his knee into George Floyd’s neck while Floyd pleaded that he couldn’t breathe, is in custody. Charges haven't yet been announced. https://nyti.ms/2TO0JqD

Text: Hundreds of protesters poured into the Minneapolis streets for a second night on Wednesday, a day after George Floyd’s death. Officers used tear gas and fired rubber bullets into the crowds. Videos showed at least one business on fire.

Text: Here's what we know about the death of George Floyd, 46, who died after being handcuffed and pinned to the ground by a Minneapolis police officer who pressed his knee into Floyd's neck

Text: The FBI and Minnesota law enforcement authorities are investigating the arrest of George Floyd, a black man who died after being pinned to the ground by an officer’s knee. Hundreds of people gathered in Minneapolis to protest the conduct of the officers.

Text: Three US police officers seen watching as another knelt on George Floyd's neck also face charges, documents show

Text: Death of George Floyd in US police custody was homicide, official post-mortem examination says
